out at the lights of his small town.  He'd been there since he could remember, and he would soon turn eighteen, the age at which boys coming of age must venture out into the unmarked territories to prove themselves worthy of manhood.  If they could travel to the great mountains, retrieve a scale from the hide of morgan, a red dragon who protects the great mountains.  Then, if they can survive the journey back, they will be praised as men.  Arol thought back to the last fall, when the last boys went on their journey.  Only two made it back.  He was afraid, but knew he must go on the journey, those who refused were hanged in front of the town, and he did not want that.  &quot;Arol!&quot;  He was quickly jolted from his thoughts by the shouts of his mother, Feron.  &quot;Arol come to bed!&quot;  Arol ran down the grassy hill toward his house.  He would worry about the future when it came. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/unitetimeweirdo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nitetimeweirdo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fresh Meat</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/20/02 9:12:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=512.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.net/nitetimehero/cheese.jpg height=120 width=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: nice</span><hr size=1> The next day, Arol left early.  He didn't want to keep the town's best metal worker, Jin, waiting.  Being a friend of the family, he offered to help Arol make a weapon, and teach him to use it.  His excitement was building, as he rounded the corner of Industrial Street, running right into an open door.  Out walked his best friend Chise.  &quot;Ouch, you ok.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah, you ready to work today?&quot; asked Arol.  Some how the 16 year old had conned Jin into helping him as well.  <br>
<br>
Chise was about 5'11&quot; with short, clean brown hair and a commanding presence.  Chise was the kind of person who liked to be in control, almost a perfectionist at times.  He couln't wait to be considered a man, even knowing what danger lay ahead.  He was leaving with Arol, a year early.  Besides, he had been trained in his grandfather's dojo.  Mastering his art at a very young age, no one in the town would stop him.   <br>
<br>
&quot;Let's get going.  Jin won't be happy If were Late.&quot;       <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uascendedbob.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ascended Bob</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/22/02 7:01:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=512.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: nice</span><hr size=1>      Arol noticed that Chise was trying hard to contain laughter. &quot;Whats so funny?&quot; he asked, trying to look stern though he realized the humor of the situation.<br>
     &quot;Nothing, lets go,&quot; said Chise.<br>
     The trip to Jin's was much less interesting than they thought it would be, and eneded up being much more work than they cared to spend that day. the afternoon, though, brought a surprise that neither had expected.<br>
     The village mayor stood atop his podium in the center of town. If anything required such measures to get attention in a town so small, you could be sure that it was important.<br>
     &quot;Though we may trimuph over man and beast. The most holy forces of nature are none to be reckoned with. There will be no hunt for the great dragon this day, for a storm in nigh and we must prepare.<br>
     The two looked to the sky to see what tidings it brought of this and saw only blue. &quot;What could he mean?&quot; asked Chise, youthful vigor angered at the thought of being smitten. &quot;We have to go. This is a test of manhood, not some silly custom. We need to do this.&quot; At that he left Arol standing in the street, half releived that he could breathe another day as a child, half anxious for him to start his real life.<br>
     He walked home, still noticing nothing odd with the weather. It was then that he saw Chise, loaded with as many weapons as he could carry.<br>
     Chise was a fearsome foe, unassailabe to all who crossed him but, Arol could not help but wonder what all of the weapons were for. <br>
     He approached Chise. &quot;Where are you going,&quot; he asked, wary of the look of determination on Chise's face. He knew that anything Chise was planning he would not be talked out of but feeling that he should at least try.<br>
     &quot;I'm going for it Arol. I am going to get a scale from that beast or die trying.&quot;<br>
     &quot;Chise, you are still a year from being of age to even attempt this. I do not even know why you want to go so early.&quot; Arol watched the unchanging countenance of his friend.<br>
     &quot;I want to. I need to prove myself to. . . well, myself,&quot; replied Chise as he continued on the path leading out of the village, with Arol close behind. &quot;Ther won't be any storm,&quot; he said. &quot;Just look at the sky.&quot;<br>
     Just then a grey started creeping around the horizon.<br>
