<br>
&quot;Look, it's not so bad.  We can just leave after the storm ends.  You'll have you're shot soon enough.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, I'm still going.&quot;  His look of determination changing to a smile.  Lightning flashed, followed by the boom of thunder.  &quot;Heh, that which is dangerous to us must also be dangerous to the beast!  It' s the perfect time to go.&quot;  He retrieved the the star and started walking swiftly down the street.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wait, Chise you can't...&quot;  Chise turned around.  Anger beginning to show.<br>
<br>
&quot;Look, either get your stuff, or head home.  If you aren't a man yet, fine.  This is something I have to do.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Like I was saying, You can't go without supplies.  The food is at my place.&quot;    <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uascendedbob.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ascended Bob</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/23/02 11:57:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=512.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: nice</span><hr size=1>      &quot;Let's go,&quot; said Arol. They walked to his house watching people scurrying like ants in the presence of such tidings as this storm. Boards were being put up and horses let loose. &quot;Wait,&quot; Arol said while stopping abruptly. &quot;Chise you have to go to my house by yourself.&quot;<br>
     &quot;What?&quot; asked Chise. &quot;What for? What will I tell your mother.?&quot;<br>
     &quot;The supplies are in the shed in the back so my mother will never even see you. Now give me the weapons and go.&quot; Arol took the heavy bag and slung it over his shoulder. &quot;Meet me at the Southern Pass and we will make way to the mountains, and hurry!&quot;<br>
     Chise was curious and a bit taken back but, Arol <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> was</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> older so he did as he was told. When he got to the small stream that ran through the northern part of the village and right in front of Arol's house he slowed his pace and looked for any sight of Feron.<br>
     Arol's mother was going about as if nothing were wrong. The miller who lived next door, though, was assisting in ever way that he could. <br>
     &quot;Now's the time,&quot; he thought. Chise snuck slowly through the brush until he was where he needed to be. Hopefully he could leave undetected as well. Finding the food that Arol spoke of was not so easy. This was because there was no food anywhere in the shed.<br>
     &quot;Feron where should I put these bags?&quot; he heard coming from the front of the house.<br>
     &quot;Oh great,&quot; he thought. &quot;They've moved all the damn food. What the hell am I. . .&quot; He stopped dead mid-sentence. Arols mother was walking around the corner of the house and straight for the shed. &quot;What am I going to do.&quot;<br>
     &quot;Oh just lay them in the kitchen,&quot; replied Arol's mother to the miller's question.&quot; She then walked into the shed. &quot;What in the world. . .&quot; She picked up the peices of a shredded broom. &quot;I just made this thing,&quot; she said. &quot;I wonder what happened?&quot; <br>
     Chise was not around for any of this. He'd taken the the small moment that her head was turned to jump out the small shed window and into Arol's room. &quot;Thank Gelendar that was close,&quot; he said while breathing hardly. He slumped down under the window to catch his breath and noticed that the kitchen was right out the door of this very room.<br>
     &quot;Do I dare?&quot; he asked with a smile. That very smile could send chills through the boldest of men. The youth that is Chise is never one to be timid. &quot;He grabbed a bad of food and was out the same way he came in.<br>
     Arol stood at the Southern Pass. Chlenching his cloak tighter against his body to ward off the chill that came with the cooling winds. His teeth were clenched as were his fists. Chise saw that he no longer carried the weapons and immediately asked after them.<br>
     &quot;Where is our gear?&quot; he asked in a somewhat irritated tone. &quot;You don't know what I went through to get this,&quot; he said, dropping the sack of rifled goods. &quot;If you think that you hiding the weapons is going to keep me from leaving  you're wrong.&quot;<br>
     &quot;Calm down Chise. They are in the cave up the road a bit.&quot;<br>
     &quot;Oh,&quot; Chise felt ashamed of his accusing tone.&quot;Sorry.&quot;<br>
     &quot;Forget it lets just go.&quot;<br>
     As they walked along, the road began to get more rocky. They were leaving the flatter lands and headed into the mountains. It would be a short journey with only a few villages, even smaller that their own to pass through. Chise tuned to Arol, &quot;By the way, what were you doing while I risked life, limb, and capture by your mother?&quot;<br>
     &quot;You'll see,&quot; said Arol. With that he veered off the path a bit. &quot;Come on the weapons are this way.&quot;<br>
     As they approachesd a small space between two hills. Chise noticed the weapons on the ground and &quot;Horses?&quot; he asked, giddy with disbeleif and glee. &quot;Now we won't have to walk.&quot;<br>
     &quot;Well, when the end of the storm comes there will be a few people wondering what happened to their horses,&quot; said Arol.<br>
     &quot;Hah, I thought I'd be the one to do something like that,&quot; said Chise. <br>
     With that they saddled up and prepared to take off.  <br>
